In recent years, global transmission of infectious diseases, such as severe acute respiratory syndromes (SARS) [1], influenza A (H1N1) flu [2], avian influenza [3], Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) [4], Ebola virus disease [5], and zika [6], has been threatening human beings. Great attention has been paid to the effects of human mobility on disease transmission.

In order to study the global spread of infectious diseases, researchers applied a metapopulation model to infectious diseases [7, 8]. The concept of metapopulation was put forward by Levins [9, 10] for the first time to investigate the processes of local extinction, recolonization and regional persistence of populations, which means “the population of populations”. With the development of network transmission dynamics, the metapopulation model has been successfully applied to understand the transmission dynamics of spatially structured populations with well-defined social units (on a scale of countries, regions, cities, small as towns, villages, families) connected through individuals’ mobility on networks, named “metapopulation networks” (see Fig. 1). 

